### Resistors in parallel

Consider 2 resistors, \(R_{i}\) and \(R_{2}\), connected in parallel, as shown in Fig. 3,

The p.d. \(V\) across both resistors is the same because they are across the same 2 points A and B. Hence,

\(I_{1}=\dfrac{V}{R_{1}}\) (3)

\(I_{2}=\dfrac{V}{R_{2}}\) (4)

To find the combined resistance of \(R_{i}\) and \(R_{2}\), re-draw Fig. 3 using a single combined resistance \(R\) between the points A and B. If the total current \(I\) is flowing between the points A and B, then the effective resistance \(R\) is given by

\(I=\dfrac{V}{R}\) (5)

In the parallel circuit, the total current is the sum of the individual currents

\(I=I_{1}+I_{2}\) (6)

Combining equations (3), (4), (5) into (6),

\(\dfrac{V}{R}\)=\(\dfrac{V}{R_{1}}+\dfrac{V}{R_{2}}\)

Cancelling \(V\), we can easily calculate the combined resistance using:

\(\dfrac{1}{R}\)=\(\dfrac{1}{R_{1}}+\dfrac{1}{R_{2}}\) (7)

This equation can be extended to as many resistors as there are in parallel.

\(\dfrac{1}{R}\)=\(\dfrac{1}{R_{1}}+\dfrac{1}{R_{2}}+\)... + \(\dfrac{1}{R_{N}}\) (8)

(where \(N\) is number of resistors connected in parallel)

Note: The effective resistance is always less than the smallest resistance in the parallel network.

