### The Potential divider principle

By connecting 2 wires with 2 terminals across one of the 2 resistors, say \(R_{i}\), the p.d. across \(R_{i}\) can be obtained. This p.d. \(V_{i}\) can be easily adjusted by varying the ratio of \(R_{i}\) and \(R_{2}\). \(V_{i}\) therefore becomes a variable source of p.d. The circuit above is call the potential divider as it divides the e.m.f. source \(E\) across resistors \(R_{i}\) and \(R_{2}\). Apply \(V=IR\) to obtain the following 2 equations:

\(E=I\left(R_{i}+R_{2}\right)\) (1) \(V_{i}=IR_{i}\) (2) \(\frac{(2)}{(1)}\) \(\Rightarrow\)\(\frac{V_{i}}{E}=\frac{R_{i}}{R_{i}+R_{2}}\)

Hence we get \(V_{i}=\frac{R_{i}}{R_{i}+R_{2}}\times E\)

Note that \(V_{i}\) depends on the ratio \(\frac{R_{i}}{R_{i}+R_{2}}\).

