### Variable p.d. using light dependent resistors and thermistors

* _Candidates should be able to explain the use of thermistors and light dependent resistors in potential divider circuits to provide a potential difference which is dependent on temperature and illumination respectively._ In Example 7, a rheostat is used to provide a variable output p.d. Devices like LDRs and thermistors can also provide variable output p.d. This is because the resistance of the LDR changes with light intensity, and the resistance of the thermistor changes with temperature.

#### 3.2.1 Light dependent resistor (LDR) or photoconductive cell

Recall that the resistance of a LDR decreases as light intensity (illumination) falling on it increases.

Fig. 5 and Fig. 6 show 2 ways of using a LDR to obtain a variable p.d. which varies according to light intensity. Each circuit serves a different purpose.

Burdar Alarm

In Fig. 5, two wires connected across the fixed resistor give a \(V_{\text{output}}\) of

\[V_{\text{output}}=\frac{R}{R_{\text{L}}+R}\times E\]

During a break in at night, if the burglar's torch shines light on the LDR, \(R_{\text{L}}\) decreases. Hence \(V_{\text{output}}\) increases. If this \(V_{\text{output}}\) is applied across a siren, the siren will be activated when \(V_{\text{output}}\) reaches a certain value.

Auto-ON night light

Fig. 6, two wires connected across the LDR give a \(V_{\text{output}}\) of

\[V_{\text{output}}=\frac{R_{\text{L}}}{R_{\text{L}}+R}\times E\]

As the sun sets, light intensity decreases and \(R_{\text{L}}\) increases. Hence \(V_{\text{output}}\) across the LDR increases. If this \(V_{\text{output}}\) is applied across a lamp, it will light up when \(V_{\text{output}}\) reaches a certain value.

#### 3.2.2 Thermistors

Recall that a thermistor (or thermally sensitive resistor) is made of a semiconductor material which has resistance that changes according to the surrounding temperature.

For a thermistor with a negative temperature coefficient, its resistance \(R_{\mathrm{T}}\) decreases as temperature increases.

Fig. 7 and Fig. 8 show 2 ways of using a thermistor to obtain a variable p.d. which varies according to temperature. Each circuit serves a different purpose.

Temperature detection fire alarm

Fig. 7, two wires connected across the fixed resistor give a \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) of

\[V_{\mathrm{output}}=\frac{R}{R_{\mathrm{T}}+R}\times E\]

During a fire, the temperature increases and \(R_{\mathrm{T}}\) decreases. Hence \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) across the fixed resistor increases. If this \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) is applied across a siren, the siren will be activated when \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) reaches a certain value.

Ice and snow melting device for frost protection

Fig. 8, two wires connected across the thermistor give a \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) of

\[V_{\mathrm{output}}=\frac{R_{\mathrm{T}}}{R_{\mathrm{T}}+R}\times E\]

During winter, the temperature decreases and \(R_{\mathrm{T}}\) increases. Hence \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) across the thermistor increases. If this \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) is applied across a heater, the heater will turn on when \(V_{\mathrm{output}}\) reaches a certain value.

